e discriminative power beyond baseline guessing.\n- Tenure is the single most predictive feature — a simple business rule emerges: customers who reach 12+ months are significantly less likely to churn.\n- Contract type matters: month-to-month customers are a distinct risk cohort worth targeting with retention offers early in their lifecycle.\n:::\n\n---\n\n## Reflection\n\nWhat surprised me here was how much signal was already baked into fairly simple features. I expected to need interaction terms or more complex feature engineering, but the Random Forest extracted meaningful patterns from raw inputs without much coaxing.\n\nThe harder question — which I didn't answer here — is what to *do* with the prediction. A high-probability churn score only helps if there's a retention action to pair with it: a discount, a proactive support call, a plan upgrade offer. The model is only as useful as the process downstream of it.\n\n<br><br>\n<a href=\"index.qmd\" class=\"btn-ghost\">← Back to Projects</a>\n\n",
